    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Delicate, laterally-flattened and shrimp-like with large black eyes and elongate, setose antennae. Nippers of legs 1 and 2 small, remaining legs unusual in that they each end in a minute claw (used to grip the sides of the burrow).</p><p>Perhaps best recognized in the field by the unusual habit of occupying semicircular burrows excavated into the surfaces of compound ascidians.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_235",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>About 5 mm</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_236",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Tropical Indian Ocean through to Namibia.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Mozambique to Namibia.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_237",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Excavate shallow burrows into the surfaces of compound ascidians, within which they lie upside down, with the legs pointing upwards. The pleopods are then beaten to create a water current from which food particles are filtered. The small claws on the walking legs are used to grip the sides of the burrows and to close these when disturbed. Can be very common, with several individuals per square centimeter of host surface.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_238",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Presumed to pump water through the burrow by constant beating of the abdominal appendages (pleopods) and to filter food particles from the water stream using the setose antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_239",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>As with all amphipods, the eggs are extruded into a marsupial chamber beneath the legs of females, where they are fertilized by the male and develop into fully formed young before being released.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_240",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are some 25 species in this genus, all with similar habits, but this is the only one found in the region. No other regional amphipod species occupy this unusual habitat.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_241",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
